 <bibl  n='urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0026.tlg001' type='cts-urn'>Aeschin. 1</bibl>
 </head>
 <p >(<name  type='ancientAuthor'>Aeschines</name>, <title >Against <name  type='person'>Timarchus</name></title>, see also <name  n='oratory' type='ancientGenre'>Oratory</name>). This is a speech that <name  type='ancientAuthor'>Aeschines</name>
 composed and delivered in a trial before a <term  sortKey='lawcourt'>jury</term>. In
 <date  when='-0346'>346 BCE</date>, <name  type='ancientAuthor'>Aeschines</name> and <name  type='ancientAuthor'>Demosthenes</name> served together on an embassy to <name  type='person'>Philip</name> of <placeName  key='Macedon'>Macedon</placeName>. The subject
 of the embassy was an alliance between <placeName  key='Athens'>Athens</placeName> and
 <name  type='person'>Philip</name>, and protection for <placeName  key='Phocis'>Phocis</placeName>, an ally of <placeName  key='Athens'>Athens</placeName> that was at
 war with <placeName  key='Thebes'>Thebes</placeName>. The embassy was not a success, and in
 <date  when='-0345'>345 BCE</date>
 <name  type='ancientAuthor'>Demosthenes</name> and <name  type='person'>Timarchus</name>
 brought charges of treason against <name  type='ancientAuthor'>Aeschines</name>, claiming
 that he had been bribed to betray Athenian interests to <name  type='person'>Philip</name>
 (Source for date: <bibl >E. M. Harris, <title >Aeschines and Athenian Politics</title>
 [Oxford, 1995]</bibl>). In order to delay his own treason trial, <name  type='ancientAuthor'>Aeschines</name> brought charges against <name  type='person'>Timarchus</name>, alleging that he had been a prostitute, which was illegal for an
 Athenian Citizen. <name  type='ancientAuthor'>Demosthenes</name> defended <name  type='person'>Timarchus</name> (that speech is lost), but <name  type='ancientAuthor'>Aeschines</name> won his case. Thus, <name  type='ancientAuthor'>Aeschines</name>’ tactic worked, and <name  type='ancientAuthor'>Demosthenes</name> (alone) waited until 343 BCE to resume his prosecution (see <bibl  n='urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0026.tlg002' type='cts-urn'>Aeschin. 2</bibl>, <bibl  n='urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0014.tlg019' type='cts-urn'>Dem. 19</bibl>). (See also the genre
 <name  type='ancientGenre'>Oratory</name>.)</p>
